1
00:00:04,613 --> 00:00:05,494
To write about a flower,

2
00:00:05,761 --> 00:00:06,907
to dramatize a flower,

3
00:00:07,461 --> 00:00:08,914
I have to show the flower's arc.

4
00:00:09,535 --> 00:00:11,889
And the flower's arc stretches back to the beginning of life.

5
00:00:12,862 --> 00:00:13,966
How did this flower get here?

6
00:00:14,613 --> 00:00:15,406
What was its journey?

7
00:00:16,602 --> 00:00:17,196
Therefore,

8
00:00:17,790 --> 00:00:19,330
I should infer from analogy

9
00:00:20,133 --> 00:00:24,332
that probably all the organic beings which have ever lived on this earth

10
00:00:26,063 --> 00:00:30,275
have descended from some one primordial form

11
00:00:31,495 --> 00:00:33,454
into which life was first breathed.

12
00:00:34,614 --> 00:00:35,856
It is a journey of evolution.

13
00:00:36,116 --> 00:00:36,722
Adaptation.

14
00:00:37,564 --> 00:00:38,539
The journey we all take.

15
00:00:39,026 --> 00:00:40,812
A journey that unites each and every one of us.

16
00:00:41,858 --> 00:00:45,144
Darwin writes that we all come from the very first single-cell organism.

17
00:00:45,813 --> 00:00:46,466
Yet here I am.

18
00:00:47,501 --> 00:00:48,274
And there's Laroche.

19
00:00:48,961 --> 00:00:49,528
There's Orlean.

20
00:00:50,263 --> 00:00:51,075
And there's the ghost orchid.

21
00:00:52,129 --> 00:00:53,357
All trapped in our own bodies,

22
00:00:53,941 --> 00:00:54,839
in moments in history.

23
00:00:55,873 --> 00:00:56,219
That's it.

24
00:00:57,238 --> 00:00:58,138
That's what I need to do.

25
00:00:59,432 --> 00:01:00,657
Tie all of history together.

26
00:01:03,185 --> 00:01:04,930
Start right before life begins on the planet.

27
00:01:06,137 --> 00:01:06,590
All is...

28
00:01:07,512 --> 00:01:07,960
lifeless.

29
00:01:08,132 --> 00:01:09,526
And then, like, life begins,

30
00:01:09,779 --> 00:01:10,173
um,

31
00:01:10,491 --> 00:01:11,235
with organisms.

32
00:01:11,481 --> 00:01:12,552
Those single-cell ones.

33
00:01:12,660 --> 00:01:15,499
Oh, and it's before sex, because, like, everything was asexual.

34
00:01:15,805 --> 00:01:17,621
From there we go to bigger things.

35
00:01:17,646 --> 00:01:18,322
Jellyfish.

36
00:01:18,541 --> 00:01:21,193
Then that fish that got legs and crawled out on the land.

37
00:01:21,273 --> 00:01:24,234
And then we see, you know, like, dinosaurs.

38
00:01:24,661 --> 00:01:26,375
Then they're around for a long time.

39
00:01:26,497 --> 00:01:29,504
Then an asteroid comes and "phwar!"

40
00:01:29,604 --> 00:01:32,571
The insects, the mammals, the primates, monkeys.

41
00:01:33,087 --> 00:01:33,869
The simple monkeys.

42
00:01:34,513 --> 00:01:36,643
The old-fashioned monkeys giving way to the new monkeys.

43
00:01:36,727 --> 00:01:39,004
Whatever. And then apes. Whatever. And man.

44
00:01:39,344 --> 00:01:41,045
Then we see the whole history of human civilization,

45
00:01:41,258 --> 00:01:46,100
hunting, gathering, farming, war, love, religion, heartache, disease, loneliness, technology.

46
00:01:46,333 --> 00:01:48,368
We bring it all the way to this moment in history and

47
00:01:48,602 --> 00:01:50,382
end with Susan Orlean in her office at The New Yorker

48
00:01:50,439 --> 00:01:51,881
writing about flowers, and bang!

49
00:01:52,021 --> 00:01:52,814
The movie begins.

50
00:01:53,067 --> 00:01:53,600
This is great.

51
00:01:53,727 --> 00:01:55,213
This is the breakthrough I've been hoping for.

52
00:01:55,286 --> 00:01:56,753
It's never been ...

53
00:01:57,085 --> 00:01:58,233
She's a genius!

